            <h2 class="section-title mt-4 text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.01em]">
              Deterministic sealing: why canonicalization matters
            </h2>
            <p class="mt-4 text-slateblue leading-relaxed measure">
              Integrity claims depend on deterministic inputs to hashing and signing. If the artifact’s representation can vary across environments, integrity verification becomes brittle.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="col-span-12 lg:col-span-8">
            <div class="border hairline no-rounded overflow-hidden reveal">
              <div class="px-6 py-4 border-b hairline bg-vellum">
                <div class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-slateblue/90">[SEALING PIPELINE]</div>
              </div>

              <div class="divide-y" style="border-color: rgba(71,85,105,0.22);">
                <div class="grid grid-cols-12 px-6 py-4 gap-4">
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4 font-mono text-[11px] text-slateblue/90 uppercase tracking-[0.16em]">Canonicalize</div>
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                    JSON artifacts are canonicalized prior to hashing (e.g., RFC 8785 for JSON canonicalization) to preserve deterministic integrity across heterogeneous systems.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="grid grid-cols-12 px-6 py-4 gap-4">
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4 font-mono text-[11px] text-slateblue/90 uppercase tracking-[0.16em]">Hash</div>
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                    A cryptographic digest is computed over the canonical form to create a stable integrity fingerprint.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="grid grid-cols-12 px-6 py-4 gap-4">
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4 font-mono text-[11px] text-slateblue/90 uppercase tracking-[0.16em]">Sign</div>
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                    The digest is signed under an operator-controlled key posture (non-custodial by design). Signatures support tamper-evidence and provenance.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="grid grid-cols-12 px-6 py-4 gap-4">
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4 font-mono text-[11px] text-slateblue/90 uppercase tracking-[0.16em]">Verify</div>
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                    Authorized parties verify the signature against the canonicalized artifact and published verification material without requiring model weights or proprietary architecture.
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="mt-8 border hairline p-6 no-rounded reveal">
              <div class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-slateblue/90">[KEY CUSTODY]</div>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                NADIR is designed for non-custodial operation: signing keys are generated and retained within the operator environment (HSM/KMS where available). NADIR does not require possession or transmission of private keys.
              </p>
            </div>
